Known bugs and fragile areas.


JIT VECTOR PATH MAY READ PAST BUFFER BOUNDS

The JIT's vector loop processes K elements at a time (K=4 ARM64, K=8 x86).
The branch to the scalar tail correctly checks remaining >= K, but the
preamble also runs vector-width ops on uniform values loaded from buffers.
When a buffer is smaller than K * element_size bytes, vector loads (LDR Q,
VMOVDQU) read past the allocation.

This is usually harmless (excess lanes are unused), but ASan redzones or
page-boundary allocations can cause intermittent SEGV.  Guard pages after
JIT code allocations help detect code overruns but don't fix data overreads.
